## What we learned the hard way

Don't over-engineer versioning for a pre-1.0 project. Git already is version control.

### The scale
  Branch name          → 'am I on stable or experimental?' (free, already exists)
  git describe         → 'exactly what commit am I on?' (free, already exists)
  mycelium.sh --version → human-friendly wrapper around git describe (we added this)
  Semver tags          → 'this is a milestone others can depend on' (use sparingly)

### Semver pre-release labels (when you actually need them)
  alpha  — exploring, might not ship (where multi-repo is NOW)
  beta   — feature-complete, testing with real users
  rc     — believed ready, final validation
  (none) — shipped, confident

### What to actually do
  Exploring a feature?  Stay on the branch. Don't tag.
  Feature validated?    Merge to main. Tag if it's a real milestone.
  Need to share pre-release? Tag as v0.3.0-alpha.1. Not v0.3.0.

### Mistakes made
  v0.2.0 was tagged after tests passed but before anyone used export/import for real.
  The code is fine. The tag was premature. We added release engineering infrastructure
  (installer stamping, CI version checks, constraint notes about semver) before we had
  anything to release. The branch was the right tool. We abandoned it too early.

### Going forward
  Branches = exploration. Tags = milestones. git describe = identity.
  Don't tag until real usage confirms value.
